<seg id=1> Chuan Leekpai: Thailand Will Advance Its General Election </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> (Bangkok) Thai Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai said the night before that he would advance the general election before the 7-party united government's term of office expires in October 2000. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> However, he added that the united government is currently stable, capable of carrying out economic reform plans. </seg>
<seg id=4> He said that this kind of economic reform was of vital importance to revitalizing economy and reaching the goal of maintainable growth level. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> Chuan Leekpai said when delivering a speech at the dinner of Thai Overseas Journalists Club, "Foreign investors' confidence is closely related with the stability of government and consistence of policies, we will remember this point well." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> "We won't stay to the expiration of term of office. </seg>
<seg id=7> However much time left on hand we will use the time to work hard to really reform the national economy, to lay a solid foundation for (future) sustainable development." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> Chuan Leekpai expressed that it was not decided yet when to dismiss the Congress and hold the general election in advance. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> Thailand is not out of crisis. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=10> Additionally, Chuan Leekpai also warned in his speech that Thailand was not out of crisis. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=11> He pointed out that the present situation is still "fragile"; global factors might cause Thailand to stray away from the goal of economic turnaround in the second half of 1999. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=12> However, he vowed to implement reform measures in a very wide scope and eradicate the prevalent corruption undermining Thailand's economy. </seg>
</p>
